<setup>
  <selectFromSequence name="k" from="0.5" to="2" step="0.5" exclude="1"/>
  <selectFromSequence name="z" from="2" to="4" step="1"/>
  <selectFromSequence name="y" from="-4" to="-2" step="1"/>

  <math name="w">$k*$z^2/4</math>
  <math name="m">$k*$z/2</math>

  <function name="f">-1*$k*x*(x-$z)</function>
  <function name="g">$m*x</function>
  
  <function name="R1">$f - $y</function>
  <function name="r1">$g - $y</function>
  <function name="R2">$w - $g</function>
  <function name="r2">$w - $f</function>
  
  <function name="g1"> pi*(($R1)^2 - ($r1)^2)</function>
  <function name="G1"> pi*($k^2/5*x^5 - $k^2*$z/2*x^4 + ($k^2*$z^2+2*$k*$y-$m^2)/3*x^3 - ($k*$y*$z-$m*$y)*x^2)</function>

  <function name="g2"> pi*(($R2)^2 - ($r2)^2)</function>
  <function name="G2"> pi*(-$k^2/5*x^5 + $k^2*$z/2*x^4 - ($k^2*$z^2+2*$k*$w-$m^2)/3*x^3 + ($k*$w*$z-$m*$w)*x^2)</function>
  
  <math name="a">0</math>
  <math name="b">$z/2</math>
  
  <math name="intValue1" simplify>$$G1($b)-$$G1($a)</math>
  <math name="intValue2" simplify>$$G2($b)-$$G2($a)</math>

  <mathList name="intPoints">(0,0) ($z/2, $k*$z^2/4)</mathList>

</setup>  

  <p>
    Consider the finite region, <m>\mathcal{R}</m>, that is bounded by the curves 
    <me>y = <math simplify>$m x</math>, \ y = <math simplify>-$k x</math>(x-$z)</me>  
  </p>

  <p> 
    <ol marker="a.">
      <li>
        <p>
          Sketch a graph of the region, <m>\mathcal{R}</m>, and find the exact locations of the intersection points of the two curves.  Enter the intersection points as ordered pairs; separate multiple points with commas.
        </p>
        <p>
          The curves intersect at the points: <answer unorderedCompare simplifyOnCompare>$intPoints</answer>
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Find an integral expression that represents the volume of the resulting solid of revolution when <m>\mathcal{R}</m> is revolved about the line <m>y = $y</m>.  Do so by filling in the blanks below; once you identify the lower and upper limits of integration, those numbers will appear in the integral expression below.
        </p>

        <p>
          lower limit of integration: <m>a = </m> <answer name="lower">$a</answer>
        </p>
        <p>
          upper limit of integration: <m>b = </m> <answer name="upper">$b</answer>
        </p>

        <p>
          Integral expression for the volume, <m>V</m>, of the solid of revolution when revolved about <m>y = $y</m>: 
        </p>
        <p>
          <m>V = \displaystyle\int_{$lower}^{$upper}</m><mathInput name="int1" minWidth="100" /><m>d</m><mathInput name="dWhat" minWidth="15"/><answer simplifyOnCompare><award><when>$int1 = $g1 and $dWhat = x</when></award></answer> 
        </p> 
        <p>
          Evaluate the integral to find the numerical value of the volume, <m>V</m>, and report the value below.  Report your result to an accuracy within <m>0.0001</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          <m>V = </m><mathInput name="intVal1" minWidth="40" /> <answer allowedErrorInNumbers="0.0001" allowedErrorIsAbsolute><award><when>$intValue1=$intVal1 </when></award></answer>
        </p>  
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Now find an integral expression that represents the volume of the resulting solid of revolution when <m>\mathcal{R}</m> is instead revolved about the line <m>y = <math simplify displayDecimals="4">$w</math></m>.  Do so by filling in the blanks below; once you identify the lower and upper limits of integration, those numbers will appear in the integral expression below.
        </p>

        <p>
          lower limit of integration: <m>c = </m> <answer name="lower">$a</answer>
        </p>
        <p>
          upper limit of integration: <m>d = </m> <answer name="upper">$b</answer>
        </p>

        <p>
          Integral expression for the volume, <m>W</m>, of the solid of revolution when revolved about <m>y=<math simplify displayDecimals="4">$w</math></m>: 
        </p>
        <p>
          <m>W = \displaystyle\int_{$lower}^{$upper}</m><mathInput name="int2" minWidth="100" /><m>d</m><mathInput name="dWhat2" minWidth="15"/><answer allowedErrorInNumbers="0.01" allowedErrorIsAbsolute simplifyOnCompare><award><when>$int2 = $g2 and $dWhat2 = x</when></award></answer> <!--, <m>$$f($h), $$g($h), $f - $g</m> \pi \left(\left(3.375-2.25x\right)^2-\left(3.375+1.5x\left(x-3\right)\right)^2\right) -->
        </p> 
        <p>
          Evaluate the integral to find the numerical value of the volume, <m>W</m>, and report the value below.  Report your result to an accuracy within <m>0.0001</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          <m>W = </m><mathInput name="intVal2" minWidth="40" /> <answer allowedErrorInNumbers="0.0001" allowedErrorIsAbsolute><award><when>$intValue2=$intVal2 </when></award></answer>
        </p>  
      </li>      
    </ol>
  </p>